  <detection>
    - Monitor for encrypted data modification attempts
    - Check for unusual cookie lengths
    - Implement authentication at server side
    - Use authenticated encryption (GCM, not CBC)
    - Validate decrypted data integrity
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Identify CBC-encrypted data
    - Successfully modify encrypted content
    - Bypass authentication via bit flipping
    - Change user roles in encrypted tokens
    - Document exploitable fields
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - CBC without MAC is always vulnerable to bit flipping
    - First block can be modified via IV manipulation
    - Block size is typically 16 bytes (AES) or 8 bytes (3DES)
    - Padding oracle + bit flipping = full encryption/decryption
    - Modern systems should use authenticated encryption (AES-GCM)
    - Test with single-bit changes first to understand structure
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>CBC bit flipping is a fundamental cryptographic attack that works without knowing the key. If you can modify ciphertext and see the decrypted result (or observe application behavior), you can likely manipulate the plaintext. The key insight: XORing ciphertext block N-1 XORs plaintext block N. Every CBC implementation without authentication is potentially vulnerable.</remember>
